    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-03-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-03-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="96"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d96">
                <head>96. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d96fn0"
                        >Source: Department of State, Central Files, 751.5621 /3–359. Confidential.
                        Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MBRH1">McBride</persName> and approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName> on March 9.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1959-03-03">March 3, 1959</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_AH1">Herve Alphand</persName>, French
                        Embassy</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Livingston T. Merchant</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MBRH1">Robert H. McBride</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_WE1">WE</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Atomic Submarine for France</item>
                </list>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName> called the French Ambassador
                    and said that on the instruction of the Acting Secretary he found it necessary
                    to inform the French that should they proceed with their action in withdrawing
                    their Mediterranean fleet from <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>;<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d96fn1">See <ref target="frus1958-60v07p1#d187">Part 1, Documents
                            187</ref> ff.</note> legislative justification for furnishing an atomic
                    submarine to France would appear to be removed. He said that if the French
                    action were carried out he thought the Congressional situation would be
                    extremely difficult and that it would in all likelihood prove impossible to
                    obtain passage by Congress of the necessary action. He said that he had thought
                    it was essential that the French be forewarned to this sense and that
                    accordingly he was calling him urgently on the instructions of the Acting
                    Secretary.</p>
            </div>
